Think of the most competitive situation you've been in during the past 12 months. It could be a project, organization, job, or event that felt competitive — where people around you were trying to get ahead and beat each other, rather than working together.
This situation may have brought out the worst in people, causing fairness and generosity to take a backseat to selfishness, winning, and even manipulation or sabotage. This should be a situation where you were personally involved.
In the space below, please write a few sentences describing this situation.

In the space below, please write a few sentences describing this situation.

column20: We (a team of 6) were writing each of our separate subroutines for a software application that would be used to migrate the company's data to another system. Each of us had our own competencies and specialties that we brought to the table. In previous migration projects I had worked on at other organizations, such an environment would invariably break down toward the end of the project when all the subs were meant to work seamlessly together; having not been previously (properly) tested against each the other to confirm compatibility. In this team, however, after the first 2 subs were finished, they were tested. And after each person finished their respective subs thereafter, each was tested against the others (individually and as a full set of code). Ultimately, the project finished 6 months early with a successful migration, and we all got some pretty heady kudos from management/ownership, and some pretty hefty bonuses as well. It was one of the best teams I've worked with -- if not the best -- to date anyway!!
column23: The team, almost without saying it (we didn't have a meeting to specifically say "let's test each phase as we finish each sub") decided to do just that. Everyone brought their subs in for testing against previously completed subs, incompatibilities were found, corrected and a final sub was tested and approved. It wasn't always rose colored glasses. Some subs had to be heavily re-written, but -- more times than not -- others on the team threw-in to help do the re-write. It was just an awesome thing to watch actually.
